http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Visakhapatnam/Aim-to-achieve-total-literacy-says-Ashok/article13993826.ece

Winning freedom from the British rule came with responsibilities on each one of us to carefully protect and nurture it, Union Minister of Civil Aviation P. Ashok Gajapathi Raju has said.Addressing residents as part of the third edition of Janmabhoomi - Maa Vooru at the village adopted by Anakapalle MP M. Srinivasa Rao under Saansad Adarsh Gram Yojana on Sunday, he called upon the people not to fritter away their freedom and rights by imposing their faith in people out to exploit them.Recalling the words of Mahakavi Gurajada Appa Rao, he asked everyone to set aside time and wealth for social good as nation comprises people. He called upon the people of the village to set themselves a target to achieve 100 per cent literacy by next year, and asked them to learn from the example of Chittiguruvulu of Dwarapudi village in Vizianagaram district where children took the responsibility to make their parents literate.“Janmabhoomi is a good platform for the people to come together and take a decision on activities to be taken up for larger good of society. No outsider will come in and help you. You have to initiate action yourself,” the Union Minister said.Works launchedEarlier, the Union Minister launched street lighting system in the village taken up at a cost of Rs. 40 lakh under MPLADS of Mr. Srinivasa Rao.Under Janmabhoomi, de-siltation and revival of a 47-acre tank was taken up to improve irrigation to 3,000 acres in its ayacut.The Union Minister gave away ration cards and Chandranna Sankranti Kanuka to eligible persons.